Exactly; a small style block makes it quick to generate a calm, legible layout.  
Here’s a simple CSS section you can drop into a Pandoc or Typora setup (save it as `reset-style.css` and reference it when exporting):

```css
/* ===== My Reset Plan – Print Style ===== */
body {
  font-family: 'Calibri', 'Verdana', Arial, sans-serif;
  font-size: 12pt;
  line-height: 1.6;
  background: #fafafa;
  color: #222;
  margin: 1in;
}

h1, h2, h3 {
  font-family: 'Open Sans Semibold', 'Source Sans Pro', sans-serif;
  color: #5a6b7a;
  margin-top: 1.2em;
  margin-bottom: 0.4em;
}

table {
  width: 100%;
  border-collapse: collapse;
  margin-top: 0.5em;
  margin-bottom: 1em;
}

th, td {
  border: 1px solid #cccccc;
  padding: 0.3em 0.5em;
  vertical-align: top;
}

tr:nth-child(even) {
  background: #f2f6f8;
}

blockquote {
  background: #f1f5f6;
  border-left: 4px solid #5b9a99;
  padding: 0.5em 0.8em;
  font-style: italic;
  color: #333;
}

hr {
  border: none;
  border-top: 1px solid #cccccc;
  margin: 1.5em 0;
}

@page {
  margin: 0.75in;
}
```

To apply it, use something like  
`pandoc reset-plan.md -c reset-style.css -o reset-plan.pdf`  
or select the stylesheet in Typora’s PDF export options.

